    <h2>Introduction to Data Privacy</h2>
    
    <div class="definition-box">
      <p> According to Kuye (2023): In the 21st century, data privacy stands as a critical pillar of digital trust, decisively shaping how personal information is collected, processed, and secured.</p>
      <p>As noted by Alferez et al. (2020): Regulatory frameworks like the GDPR (EU) and New Zealandâ€™s Privacy Act 2020 reflect global efforts to balance technological innovation with ethical data practices.</p>
    </div>
    <br> <br> <br>
    <h3>Understanding Personal Data</h3>
    <div class="key-points">
      <ul>
         <li><i class="fas fa-fingerprint fa-icon"></i> Personal data is any information that can identify or point to a specific individual</li>
        <li><i class="fas fa-users fa-icon"></i> Some companies may not consider information as personal if shared by multiple people (household or shared IP address)</li>
        <li><i class="fas fa-shield-alt fa-icon"></i> Protected personal data is information collected by companies unless directly provided by the individual or collected through their online activity</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    
    <h3>1.1 Importance of data privacy for individuals</h3>
    
    <div class="quote-box">
      <p><strong>As explained by Jaiswal (2024):</strong> Individuals encounter numerous obstacles in safeguarding their data privacy due to widespread online tracking and extensive collection of personal information.</p>
    </div>
    
    <div class="key-points">
      <h4>Key Challenges for Individuals:</h4>
      <ul>
        <li>Most users are unaware of the true scope of tracking despite cookie notifications</li>
        <li>Social media encourages excessive information sharing beyond user awareness</li>
        <li>Rising cybercrime (phishing, system breaches) increases risks of fraud and identity theft</li>
        <li>Requires constant vigilance and understanding of privacy practices</li>
      </ul>
      
      <h4>Why It Matters:</h4>
      <ul>
        <li>Protects against identity theft and financial fraud</li>
        <li>Maintains personal autonomy in digital spaces</li>
        <li>Prevents unauthorized use of personal information</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    
    <h3>1.2 Importance of data privacy for organizations</h3>
    
    <div class="key-points">
      <h4>Current Challenges for Organizations:</h4>
      <ul>
        <li>Collecting personal data without explicit user consent</li>
        <li>Lack of transparency about data collection and usage</li>
        <li>Increasing threats from cybercrime and data breaches</li>
        <li>Vulnerabilities from connected devices (IoT)</li>
        <li>Difficulty managing data sprawl</li>
      </ul>
      
      <h4>Essential Protections:</h4>
      <ul>
        <li>Implement strong security measures and encryption</li>
        <li>Foster a culture of privacy awareness</li>
        <li>Develop clear communication about data practices</li>
      </ul>
      
      <h4>Business Benefits:</h4>
      <ul>
        <li>Builds customer trust and brand reputation</li>
        <li>Ensures compliance with regulations (Privacy Act 2020, GDPR)</li>
        <li>Reduces risk of costly data breaches</li>
        <li>Supports long-term business success</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
